Problem Statement

Context

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

### 1. MISSING VALUE TREATMENT
# Check for missing values
print("Missing Values:\n", df.isnull().sum())

# No missing values were found in this dataset

### 2. FEATURE ENGINEERING (if needed)
# Drop non-predictive columns
df.drop(columns=["ID", "ZIPCode"], inplace=True)

# Remove logically invalid values (e.g., negative experience)
df = df[df["Experience"] >= 0]

### 3. OUTLIER DETECTION AND TREATMENT (IQR method)
for col in ["Income", "CCAvg", "Mortgage"]:
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    df = df[(df[col] >= lower_bound) & (df[col] <= upper_bound)]

### 4. FEATURE SCALING
# Scale numeric features
scaler = StandardScaler()
numeric_cols = ["Age", "Experience", "Income", "CCAvg", "Mortgage"]
df[numeric_cols] = scaler.fit_transform(df[numeric_cols])

### 5. PREPARING DATA FOR MODELING
# Split into features and target
X = df.drop(columns=["Personal_Loan"])
y = df["Personal_Loan"]

# Train-test split with stratification
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# Print shape and class balance
print("Training set shape:", X_train.shape)
print("Test set shape:", X_test.shape)
print("Training target balance:\n", y_train.value_counts(normalize=True))
print("Testing target balance:\n", y_test.value_counts(normalize=True))

# 1. Train the Logistic Regression model
model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# 2. Predict on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]  # Probability for class 1

# 3. Confusion Matrix
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
print("Confusion Matrix:\n", conf_matrix)

# 4. Classification Report
class_report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
print("\nClassification Report:\n", class_report)

# 5. ROC-AUC Score
roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)
print("\nROC AUC Score:", roc_auc)

# 6. Accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print("Accuracy:", accuracy)

# 7. Plot ROC Curve
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"ROC Curve (AUC = {roc_auc:.2f})")
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', label="Random Guess")
plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
plt.title("Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Model Performance Improvement

In[35]:
# Train initial full decision tree
full_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
full_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get pruning path and alphas
path = full_tree.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas = path.ccp_alphas

# Train a tree for each alpha
trees = []
for alpha in ccp_alphas:
    tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=alpha)
    tree.fit(X_train, y_train)
    trees.append(tree)

# Evaluate each tree using ROC AUC
auc_scores = [roc_auc_score(y_test, tree.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]) for tree in trees]

# Select best alpha
best_index = auc_scores.index(max(auc_scores))
best_alpha = ccp_alphas[best_index]
best_tree = trees[best_index]

# Predict and evaluate
y_pred = best_tree.predict(X_test)
y_prob = best_tree.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
class_report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Print evaluation results
print("Best ccp_alpha:", best_alpha)
print("Confusion Matrix:\n", conf_matrix)
print("\nClassification Report:\n", class_report)
print("Accuracy:", accuracy)
print("ROC AUC Score:", roc_auc)

# Plot ROC Curve
fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"Pruned Tree ROC (AUC = {roc_auc:.2f})", color="purple")
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
plt.title("ROC Curve - Pruned Decision Tree")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

print("\n\nPruned Decision Tree:")

# Plot the best pruned decision tree
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))  # Set figure size
plot_tree(
    best_tree,                      # The pruned decision tree model
    feature_names=X.columns,       # Column names as feature labels
    class_names=["No Loan", "Loan"], # Class labels
    filled=True,                   # Fill nodes with color
    rounded=True,                  # Rounded node boxes
    fontsize=10                    # Font size for readability
)
plt.title(f"Pruned Decision Tree (ccp_alpha = {best_alpha:.5f})")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Actionable Insights

Insight Evidence from Data
1. Higher Income = Higher Loan Acceptance The feature Income has the strongest correlation (0.50) with Personal_Loan. Customers earning >$100K/year are far more likely to accept loans.
2. Customers with CD Accounts are High Converters CD_Account shows a strong positive correlation (0.32) with loan acceptance. Many loan acceptors have an existing CD.
3. High CCAvg Users = Good Loan Candidates CCAvg (avg credit card spend) correlates at 0.36 with loan take-up. Customers who spend more via credit are more open to financing.
4. Education Level Drives Loan Interest Education level 3 (Advanced) users have 3x more loan acceptance compared to level 1 (Undergrad).
5. Age and Experience are Not Strong Predictors Weak correlation (~0) with the target. These attributes are not useful for loan targeting.
6. Highly Imbalanced Response Variable Only ~9.6% of customers took the loan implies marketing must be highly targeted to avoid waste.

Business Recommendations

  1. Focus Loan Campaigns on High-Income Segments

  • Why: They convert more than twice as often.

  • Action: Use income thresholds (e.g., $100K+) to filter mailing lists and target only high-probability customers.

  1. Target Credit Card Customers with High Monthly Spend (CCAvg)

  • Why: High CCAvg is a strong behavioral indicator of openness to loans.

  • Action: Segment and target customers with CCAvg > $3,000/month.

  1. Bundle Loan Offers with CD Accounts

  • Why: CD account holders are among the highest converters.

  • Action: Create a campaign: Already have a CD? You may pre-qualify for a personal loan.

  1. Leverage Education Level in Targeting

  • Why: Advanced-educated customers (Level 3) are most likely to take loans.

  • Action: Prioritize this segment and personalize messages with finance-savvy language.

  1. Avoid Blanket Campaigns - Use Model-Based Scoring

  • Why: With only 9.6% conversion in general population, mass campaigns would be highly inefficient.

  • Action: Deploy the trained Pruned Decision Tree to score all customers and target only those with a high predicted probability (e.g., P > 0.6).

  1. Deprioritize Age/Experience in Targeting Logic

  • Why: These attributes show little predictive value.

  • Action: Avoid using them as filtering criteria in campaigns.

  1. Monitor and Recalibrate the Model Quarterly

  • Why: Customer behavior evolves with market trends, inflation, new banking products, etc.

  • Action: Automate quarterly model evaluations and retraining pipeline.
